    },
    {
      "id": "4wZHnMiDizps19WP_0820",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -3019.380519449534,
      "y": -2897.0840144566223,
      "width": 759.0894165039062,
      "height": 580,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": "2kyJ-Z5_au1gSKGSiZd4r",
      "index": "c1t2",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2115366649,
      "version": 1304,
      "versionNonce": 697736243,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1782023284621,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "with block_size = 4:\n\nA -> [ [the , cat, sat, on] [the, mat, and, looked] [at, the, dog] ]\n\nB -> [ [A, robot, moved, through] [the, mat, and, looked] [at, the, dog] ]\n\nA[0][1] == B[0][1] \n\nfor example simple block hashing:\n\n        B1       B2     B3            B1      B2    B3\nA = [77395 , 1234 , 5678], B = [92849, 1234, 5678]\n\nbut if you use the user A cache on user B, model hallunicates  \nwhy because even the prompt is same but context here is different\n\nit might start halluncates about cats instead of robots which is very bad.\n\nCummulative hashes solves this by hashing prefix tokens\n\nhashing(blockN + block N-1)\n\nA = [77395, (77395 + 1234), ( (77395 + 1234) + 5678 ) ]\n\nso now each request holds the previous block because prefix cache is very important in KV cache.\nyour model might lose accuracy if the cache is misused here.\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "with block_size = 4:\n\nA -> [ [the , cat, sat, on] [the, mat, and, looked] [at, the, dog] ]\n\nB -> [ [A, robot, moved, through] [the, mat, and, looked] [at, the, dog] ]\n\nA[0][1] == B[0][1] \n\nfor example simple block hashing:\n\n        B1       B2     B3            B1      B2    B3\nA = [77395 , 1234 , 5678], B = [92849, 1234, 5678]\n\nbut if you use the user A cache on user B, model hallunicates  \nwhy because even the prompt is same but context here is different\n\nit might start halluncates about cats instead of robots which is very bad.\n\nCummulative hashes solves this by hashing prefix tokens\n\nhashing(blockN + block N-1)\n\nA = [77395, (77395 + 1234), ( (77395 + 1234) + 5678 ) ]\n\nso now each request holds the previous block because prefix cache is very important in KV cache.\nyour model might lose accuracy if the cache is misused here.\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
